                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d3">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11922: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-01-03T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 3, 1938—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3. Your 128, December 31, 2 p.m.,<note n="9" xml:id="d3fn9">
                        <ref target="frus1937v03#pg_847">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1937, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 847</ref>.</note> and your 1, January
                    1, 10 p.m. The Chinese Ambassador volunteered to me today statement that in his
                    interview with the President, the President made no comment upon the Japanese
                    peace terms.<note n="10" xml:id="d3fn10">See memorandum of January 3 by the
                        Secretary of State, <ref target="#pg_519">p. 519</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
